ridated water growing up, a highly anticipated, long-term study finds.", "parentTweet": false, "likes": 884}, "images": false, "linkEmbed": false, "replies": 11, "created": 1776203639000, "id": "2044172338464276990", "video": false, "poll": false, "user": {"profilePicture": "https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1811333143531540481/WVWbYBUi_normal.jpg", "displayName": "Michael Connett", "username": "michaelpconnett"}, "content": "A new study is being touted as showing no relationship between fluoridated water and IQ. But here's what you should know.\n\nThe study focuses on a population in Wisconsin that was born in 1940 -- which is five years before any communities in the U.S. began fluoridating their", "parentTweet": false, "likes": 372}}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASZQzbIeN", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 20, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8560497, "raw_content": "Before a company is able to get an H1B worker, they should have to send the job through an open market of third-party recruitment companies to fill the position with a US worker.  Recruiter gets some percentage of the hire's first year salary after 90 days on the job.  Only after THE MARKET has failed to fill a position should it be eligible for H1B...  Domestically unfillable job data is then publicly available and can inform career decisions of rising graduates...", "author": "NeverNotTrump", "created": 1776264591403, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "GhostOfTheRepublic", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "Presto TRUMPO!: H1B FIX", "last_comment_created": 1776269476744, "content": "<p>Before a company is able to get an H1B worker, they should have to send the job through an open market of third-party recruitment companies to fill the position with a US worker.  Recruiter gets some percentage of the hire's first year salary after 90 days on the job.  Only after THE MARKET has failed to fill a position should it be eligible for H1B...  Domestically unfillable job data is then publicly available and can inform career decisions of rising graduates...</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 10, "score_up": 20, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}], "status": true}